Let’s talk about elasticity! 
Elasticity often times goes unmentioned but is very important to understanding your hairs health. Hair elasticity, by definition, refers to how long a single strand of hair can stretch before it returns to its normal state. In order to find out what the elasticity of your hair is, wet a strand of hair and stretch it as much as you can. This will determine whether your hair falls under high, medium or low elasticity.

But Rese what does that mean? Why is this important?
If the hair stretches and returns to its original length when released, then elasticity is good. If there is any breakage or your hair doesn’t fall back into shape, it has low elasticity.

Also, having elasticity leaves the hair in a more pliable state, so when the cuticle is sealed, the cortex can hold on to moisture. That leaves hair with greater flexibility, and it’s easier to style. Without elasticity, hair can become frustratingly difficult to style and manage. In summary, shrinkage is a sign of good hair health. Stretched hair indicates damage. 

Lost your hairs elasticity and want to regain it? Add protein to your hair. Hair is composed of proteins. Adding such into your hair care regimen and diet will aid in strengthening the hair, thus bringing your elasticity back!

Let’s talk alopecia! Did you know that there 11 different forms of alopecia? The client above has what’s called traction alopecia. There are many types of hair loss, medically known as alopecia. Traction alopecia is caused by repeated trauma to hair follicles or from pulling your hair back into tight hairstyles.

Traction alopecia is caused by tight ponytails, braids, hair extensions, and chemical relaxers that cause tension on the scalp.

My client specifically received traction alopecia from a combination of tight braids and excessive wig usage.

If you’re skipping out on using leave-in conditioner when silk pressing hair, here’s why you shouldn’t. One of my favorite products that I can never skip is leave-in conditioner. This is essential; if the clients hair is moisturized, it will last longer and less likely result in heat damage.

When prepping hair for a silk press I use 5 product’s: scalp revitalizer, lightweight scalp oil, anti itch spray, leave-in conditioner spray and heat protectant. The most important probably being leave-in conditioner. Leave-in products provide extra moisture to the hair, protects it from damage, and helps detangle the strands. It also works to repair hair. 

*Note that leave-in conditioner and rinse out conditioner are not the same. Rinse out conditioner is meant to be rinsed after washing. It’s imperative. Failure to thoroughly do so leaves a coating on the hair that will, to you, appear to make it shinier and smooth. In reality, it has clogged your hair and coated your stands with build up which can now lead to breakage if repeated excessively.

Let’s talk about elasticity! 
Elasticity often times goes unmentioned but is very important to understanding your hairs health. Hair elasticity, by definition, refers to how long a single strand of hair can stretch before it returns to its normal state. In order to find out what the elasticity of your hair is, wet a strand of hair and stretch it as much as you can. This will determine whether your hair falls under high, medium or low elasticity.

But Rese what does that mean? Why is this important?
If the hair stretches and returns to its original length when released, then elasticity is good. If there is any breakage or your hair doesn’t fall back into shape, it has low elasticity.

Also, having elasticity leaves the hair in a more pliable state, so when the cuticle is sealed, the cortex can hold on to moisture. That leaves hair with greater flexibility, and it’s easier to style. Without elasticity, hair can become frustratingly difficult to style and manage. In summary, shrinkage is a sign of good hair health. Stretched hair indicates damage. 

Lost your hairs elasticity and want to regain it? Add protein to your hair. Hair is composed of proteins. Adding such into your hair care regimen and diet will aid in strengthening the hair, thus bringing your elasticity back!

I saw this post on my explore page today and allow me to explain what happened:

what happened here is simple. Hair sheds up to 100 strands a day. When it’s braided up the hair cannot fall after it has shed so it remained in the hair. Not to mention hair is braided with thick jam that also holds the shedded hair in place. When you take braids down you HAVE to detangle with conditioner prior to washing, it’s a must. She did not detangle her hair prior to washing it meaning any shedded hair that was still caught in her mane remained in the hair, and depending how long she kept the style in plays a factor as well. When hair gets wet it swells. The shedded strands then intertwined with the rest of her hair causing it to matte up. 

This is why I tell my clients to detangle their hair from roots to ends prior to coming in. Shedded strands caught in thick or long hair is the devil. 

3 years ago when I first started doing hair I matted up a guys hair pretty badly doing this exact thing and spent 7 hours having to get it unmatted naturally. I never made that mistake ever again. It’s a terrible lesson to learn but an essential one. We’re not all perfect but understanding how hair works goes a long way. You should be detangling your hair while taking your braids or any protective style down  prior to washing. View my story highlights for how to properly detangle your hair after a protective style based on your hair type ranging from 1-4. It’s been up for over a year now cause I keep preaching this. I suggest using fresh aloe Vera to detangling, all details are located under “MUST READ” in my highlights.

Ever heard of ‘The GreenHouse Effect’?

The main purpose of doing the greenhouse effect (GHE) is to be able to boost your hair growth by encouraging your follicles to open up through the increased blood flow as you sweat. Not only does the GHE encourage growth but it can also help to keep your hair moisturised at the same time. As your hair sweats more natural oils are released from your scalp.

If you have low porosity hair meaning that the cuticles of your hair are very tightly knitted together and therefore your hair struggles to absorb moisture the greenhouse method is perfect.

As mentioned before the greenhouse method will encourage your cuticles to open up and allow moisture to be absorbed. It’s a great way to make sure moisture is penetrated as deeply as possible into the hair shaft.

How I do use this method on my clients?
The greenhouse effect consist of fully moisturizing the hair using the LCO method then trapping that moisture in. I moisturize my clients scalp with fresh aloe vera, followed by a braid down moisturized with retention butter then scalp oiled with my Guru Growth Oil.
